-- background.mos -- scrolling-background demo, one source, many consoles.
--
-- A mosaik port of flozz's GameBoy example 06 "Graphics 3 - background"
-- (https://github.com/flozz/gameboy-examples), with a Running-Knight-style
-- walker sprite on top. The D-pad scrolls the scene (the walker strides in
-- place at the screen centre, facing the way you scroll) and START / A
-- recentres it.
--
-- One code path for all nine consoles: graphics.bkg is the same 32x32-tile
-- scrollable background everywhere, but the hardware underneath differs --
--
--   * GBDK consoles (Game Boy / Color / Analogue Pocket / Mega Duck, Sega
--     Master System / Game Gear, NES) have a real hardware tilemap layer
--     scrolled by the background scroll registers (bkg.move). 256x256 px of
--     map = one full wrap of an 8-bit scroll value, so the offsets are plain
--     u8 counters that wrap mod 256 and the map tiles seamlessly.
--
--   * The PC Engine also has a real tilemap (the VDC BAT + BXR/BYR scroll
--     registers); the 32x32 map is written twice into the 64-wide BAT so the
--     u8 scroll wraps just like on the Game Boy.
--
--   * The Atari Lynx has NO tilemap layer at all ("everything is a sprite"),
--     so its bkg engine composites only the visible window of the map (screen
--     + one tile of margin) into one small Suzy background sprite and re-blits
--     it each frame at the sub-tile scroll offset, recompositing only when the
--     camera crosses a tile boundary -- one cheap blit per frame, leaving the
--     Suzy budget free for foreground sprites. See
--     docs/reference/lynx-suzy-sprites.md for the Suzy details.
--
-- The walker is an ordinary hardware sprite layered over the background on
-- every console (Lynx: painter's order after the background blits; PCE: the
-- sprite plane in front of the BAT; GBDK: OAM over the tilemap).
--
-- Controls: D-pad scrolls; START (or A on the Lynx) recentres.

module "background" {
